Styles (manners of address) -->\n|members              = [[Raj Kaul]] <br /> [[Gangadhar Nehru]] <br /> [[Nandlal Nehru]] <br /> [[Motilal Nehru]] <br /> [[Swarup Rani Nehru]] <br /> [[Brijlal Nehru]] <br /> [[Rameshwari Nehru]] <br /> [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] <br /> [[Vijaya Lakshmi Pandit]] <br /> [[Uma Nehru]] <br /> [[Krishna Hutheesing]] <br /> [[Indira Gandhi]] <br /> [[Braj Kumar Nehru]] <br /> [[Nayantara Sahgal]]<br /> [[Feroze Gandhi]] <br /> [[Rajiv Gandhi]] <br /> [[Sanjay Gandhi]] <br /> [[Arun Nehru]] <br /> [[Sonia Gandhi]] <br /> [[Maneka Gandhi]] <br /> [[Rahul Gandhi]] <br /> [[Priyanka Vadra]] <br />[[Varun Gandhi]]<br />[[Robert Vadra]]\n|connected_members    = <!-- Notable members in selection, only if relevant in infobox and readability-wise applicable -->\n|other_families       = <!-- Connected families, typically qualified by marriage (or rarely rivalry) -->\n|distinctions         = <!-- Primarily associated distinctions such as orders, prizes, awards, etc. -->\n|traditions           = <!-- Religion, philosophy, movement, adherence, allegiance, etc. -->\n|motto                = <!-- For non-English motto, use: ''Motto in italics'' -->\n|motto_lang           = \n|motto_trans          = \n|heirlooms            = <!-- Inheritances; antiques, mementoes, jewelry, etc. -->\n|estate               = <!-- Residence, seat, etc. -->\n|website              = <!-- {{URL|example.com}}, website of the family association/foundation/memorial, etc. -->\n|footnotes            = \n}}\n\nThe '''Nehru\u2013Gandhi Family''' is an [[India]]n [[Political families of India|political family]] that has occupied a prominent place in the [[politics of India]]. The involvement of the family has traditionally revolved around the [[Indian National Congress]], as various members have traditionally led the party. Three members of the family: [[Jawaharlal Nehru]], [[Indira Gandhi]], and [[Rajiv Gandhi]], have served as the [[Prime Minister of India]], while several others have been [[Member of Parliament|members]] of [[Parliament of India|the parliament]]. \n\n''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote in 2007, \"The Nehru brand has no peer in the world \u2014 a member of the family has been in charge of India for 40 of the 60 years since independence. The allure of India's first family blends the right to rule of [[British monarchy]] with the tragic glamour of America's [[Kennedy family|Kennedy clan]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/gallery/2007/may/09/india?picture=329818381#/?picture=329818414&index=1 |title=The making of the Ghandy dynasty &#124; News &#124; guardian.co.uk |publisher=Guardian |date=9 May 2007 |accessdate=1 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Gandhi surname came from [[Feroze Gandhi]], a politician of [[Gujarati people|Gujarati]] [[Parsi]] ancestry, who changed the spelling of his surname, from Ghandy to Gandhi, after joining the [[Indian independence movement|independence movement]] to bring it in line with that of [[Mahatma Gandhi]].<ref name=\"Guha\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8FKepYC6wzwC&pg=PA33|title=India after Gandhi: The History of the World's Largest Democracy|last=Guha|first=Ramachandra|publisher=Pan Macmillan|year=2011|location=|quote=|via=|isbn=978-0330540209|at=p.&nbsp;33, footnote 2 (chapter 14)}}: \"Feroze Gandhi was also from the Nehrus' home town, Allahabad. A Parsi by faith, he at first spelt his surname 'Ghandy'. However, after he joined the national movement as a young man, he changed the spelling to bring it in line with that of Mahatma Gandhi.\"\n</ref><ref name=\"Gandhi\">{{cite book|title=Idea Exchange: Opinion Makers, Critical Issues, Interesting Times|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mkjhctAvaRAC&pg=PA87|last=Vishnu|first=Uma|publisher=Penguin Books India|year=2010|location=|quote=|via=|isbn=978-0670084890|p=87}}\n</ref> [[Indira Gandhi|Indira Priyadarshini Nehru]] (the daughter of [[Jawaharlal Nehru]]) married Feroze Gandhi in 1942 and adopted his surname.<ref>Lyon, Peter (2008) ''Conflict Between India and Pakistan: An Encyclopedia''. Santa Barbara: ABC-CLIO. p. 64. {{ISBN|978-1576077122}}. \"Feroze Gandhi was no relation of Mahatma Gandhi.\"</ref>\n\n==Family trees==\n===Earliest record===\n[[File:Anand Bhawan, Allahabad.jpg|244px|thumb|[[Anand Bhavan]], ancestral home of the Nehru-Gandhi Family in [[Allahabad]], now a museum.]]\n\n*[[Raj Kaul]] (late 1600s to early 1700s) a [[Kashmiri Pandit]], he is the earliest recorded ancestor of the Nehru family. He is believed to have moved from Kashmir to Delhi in 1716 AD. A ''[[Jagir]]'' with a house situated on the banks of a canal was granted to Raj Kaul, and, from the fact of this residence, 'Nehru' (from ''Nahar'', a canal) came to be attached to his name. ''Kaul'' was the original family name; this changed to Kaul-Nehru; and, in later years, Kaul was dropped out and the family name became only \"Nehru\".<ref>{{cite book|author=[[Shashi Tharoor]]|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Ds1RXSyRevYC&pg=PA1900&lpg=PA1900&dq=raj+kaul+nehru#v=onepage&q=raj%20kaul%20nehru&f=false|title=Nehru: The Invention of India|isbn=9789351180180|date=16 October 2007}}</ref>\n*During the early part of the 19th century, Gangadhar's father, Lakshmi Narayan Nehru, worked as a scribe in [[Delhi]] for the [[East India Company]].<ref name=\"Gupte2012\">{{cite book|author=Pranay Gupte|title=Mother India: A Political Biography of Indira Gandhi|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OOmK1lPWq80C&pg=PA139|date=February 2012|publisher=Penguin Books India|isbn=978-0-14-306826-6|pages=138\u2013139}}</ref><ref>https://www.msn.com/en-in/news/photos/the-nehru-gandhi-family-tree/ss-AAAHpxF#image=1</ref>\n\n===First generation===\n* [[Gangadhar Nehru]] (1827\u20131861), a direct descendant of Raj Kaul, he was the last ''[[Kotwal]]'' of Delhi (equivalent to Chief of Police), prior to the [[Indian Rebellion of 1857]]. He was the father of freedom fighter [[Motilal Nehru]] and grandfather of [[Jawaharlal Nehru]] who was the first [[Prime Minister of India]], thus part of the Nehru family.\n\n===Second generation===\n\n*Bansi Dhar Nehru, Gangadhar's eldest son worked in the judicial department of the British Government and, being appointed successively to various places, was partly cut off from the rest of the family.\n*[[Nandlal Nehru]] (1845\u20131887), older brother of Motilal Nehru. He was the [[Diwan (title)|Diwan]] (Prime Minister) of the [[princely state]] of [[Khetri]] in [[Rajputana]].\n*[[Motilal Nehru]] (1861\u20131931), patriarch of Nehru\u2013Gandhi family. He was a lawyer and a prominent leader of the [[Indian independence movement]]. He served as the Congress [[President of the Indian National Congress|President]] twice, 1919\u20131920 and 1928\u20131929. \n*[[Swarup Rani Nehru]] (1868\u20131938), played a prominent role in India's freedom movement in the 1920s\u201330s as an advocate of civil disobedience against the British Raj and its salt laws\n\n===Third generation===\n[[Image:Nehru family.jpg|upright|thumb| Nehru family, standing (L to R) [[Jawaharlal Nehru]], [[Vijaya Lakshmi Pandit]], [[Krishna Hutheesing]], [[Indira Gandhi]] and [[Ranjit Sitaram Pandit]]; Seated: Swaroop, [[Motilal Nehru]] and [[Kamala Nehru]] (circa 1927)]]\n*[[Jawaharlal Nehru]] (1889\u20131964), son of Motilal Nehru. He was the first [[Prime Minister of India]] and was one of the most prominent leaders of the [[Indian independence movement]]. He had succeeded his father as President of the Congress in 1929.\n*[[Vijaya Lakshmi Pandit]] (1900\u20131990), eldest daughter of Motilal Nehru. She was an Indian diplomat and politician who later became the [[President of the United Nations General Assembly]]. Married [[Ranjit Sitaram Pandit]] in 1921.\n*[[Krishna Hutheesing|Krishna Nehru Hutheesing]] (1907\u20131967) was an Indian writer, the youngest sister of Jawaharlal Nehru and Vijaya Lakshmi Pandit, and part of the Nehru\u2013Gandhi family.\n*[[Kamala Nehru]] (1899\u20131936), wife of Jawaharlal Nehru. She was a prominent social reformer{{Citation needed|reason=Your explanation here|date=October 2017}} and was an active member of the [[All India Congress Committee]].\n*[[Brijlal Nehru]] (1884-1964), son of Nandlal Nehru and a nephew of Motilal Nehru. He was the Finance Minister of the [[princely state]] of [[Jammu and Kashmir]] during the rule of Maharaja [[Hari Singh]].\n*[[Rameshwari Nehru]] (1886\u20131966), wife of Brij Lal Nehru. She was a journalist and social worker who co-founded [[All India Women's Conference]]\n*[[Ratan Kumar Nehru]] (1902-1981), civil servant and diplomate\n\n===Fourth generation===\n*[[Indira Gandhi|Indira Priyadarshini Nehru]] (later [[Indira Gandhi]]) (1917\u20131984), only daughter of Jawaharlal Nehru. She became the first woman Prime Minister of India.\n*[[Feroze Gandhi]]  (1912\u20131960), husband of Indira. He was a politician and journalist.\n*[[Braj Kumar Nehru]] (1909\u20132001), son of Brijlal Nehru. He served as the Indian diplomat and ambassador to the United States and as High Commissioner to the United Kingdom. He later served as Governor of several Indian states and was an adviser to his cousin Indira Gandhi.\n*Magdolna Nehru (1908\u20132017), nicknamed Fori, wife of Braj Kumar Nehru. \n*Balwant Kumar Nehru (1916\u20131996), son of Brijlal Nehru and brother of Braj Kumar Nehru. Engineer and corporate manager who rose to become the Deputy Chairman of ITC and the President of the All-India Management Association.\n*Sarup Nehru, wife of Balwant Kumar Nehru.\n*Harsha Hutheesing (1935\u20131991) and [[Ajit Hutheesing]] (1936\u20132017), sons of Krishna Nehru Hutheesing and Raja Hutheesing\n*Chandralekha Mehta, the eldest of the three daughters born to Jawaharlal Nehru's sister, [[Vijaya Lakshmi Pandit]]\n*[[Nayantara Sahgal]] (born 10 May 1927), the second of the three daughters born to Vijaya Lakshmi Pandit\n*Rita Dar, the youngest of the three daughters born to Vijaya Lakshmi Pandit\n\n===Fifth generation===\n[[File:Indira Gandhi, Jawaharlal Nehru, Rajiv Gandhi and Sanjay Gandhi.jpg|upright|thumb|[[Indira Gandhi]], [[Jawaharlal Nehru]], [[Rajiv Gandhi]] and [[Sanjay Gandhi]] (circa 1949).]]\n*[[Arun Nehru]], (1944-2013), great grand son of Nandlal Nehru. He was a politician and union minister during the 1980s.\n*[[Rajiv Gandhi]] (1944\u20131991), eldest son of Indira and Feroze Gandhi. He became the 7th Prime Minister of India after Indira's death.\n*[[Sanjay Gandhi]] (1946\u20131980), second son of Indira. He was also one of the most trusted lieutenants of his mother during the 1970s and was widely expected to succeed his mother as Prime Minister of India. But met with an untimely death in a plane crash.\n*[[Sonia Gandhi]] (n\u00e9e Maino 1946), widow of Rajiv Gandhi. She was born in Italy and took Indian citizenship, 11 years after marrying [[Rajiv Gandhi]]. She was the President of the [[Indian National Congress]] from 1998 to 2017 and has served as the Chairperson of the [[United Progressive Alliance]] since 2004. \n*[[Maneka Gandhi]] (n\u00e9e Anand 1956), widow of Sanjay Gandhi. She is a noted environmentalist and animal welfare activist. She is a prominent member of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]].  She has served as a cabinet minister in four government.She also served as the Indian Union Cabinet Minister for Women & Child Development in the BJP led Government of 2014-19.\n*Subhadra Nehru, wife of Arun Nehru.\n*Sunil Nehru (b.1946) -- eldest son of Balwant Kumar Nehru. Engineer and corporate strategist, senior company executive at Max India, adventurer, scuba diver, and ardent trekker.\n*Neena Nehru (b.1946 n\u00e9e Neena Heble) -- wife of Sunil Nehru. Artist, poet, architect.\n*Nikhil Nehru (b.1948) -- second son of Balwant Kumar Nehru.  He had a stellar career in advertising, rising to become the President of McCann-Erickson and Chairman of Results International Group, India.\n*Samhita Nehru\u2014wife of Nikhil Nehru.\n*Vikram Nehru (b.1952) -- third son of Balwant Kumar Nehru.  Entered the field of international development with a career at the World Bank. Became the World Bank's Chief Economist and Director for Poverty Reduction,Economic Management, Private and Financial Sector Development for East Asia and the Pacific.  Subsequently, became the Chair in Southeast Asian Studies at the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace in Washington DC and then Distinguished Practitioner-in-Residence at the Johns Hopkins University School of Advanced International Studies.\n\n===Sixth generation===\n*[[Rahul Gandhi]] (1970), son of [[Rajiv Gandhi]] and [[Sonia Gandhi]]. He was the president  of the Congress party from 2017 and 2019,<ref>{{cite news|last=Ghandy|first=Rahul |title=Rahul Gandhi gets bigger role in Congress, appointed party vice-president|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2013-01-19/india/36431467_1_rahul-ghandy-congress-party-chief-spokesperson|accessdate=19 January 2013|newspaper=The Times of India|date=20 January 2013}}</ref> and was a member of Parliament from Amethi, UP from 2004 to 2019. He was the Chairman of the Congress coordination panel for 2014 Lok Sabha polls. He is currently the MP from Wayanad, Kerala in the Lok Sabha.\n*[[Priyanka Gandhi Vadra]] (n\u00e9e Gandhi, 1972), daughter of Rajiv Gandhi and Sonia Gandhi. Priyanka is married to [[Robert Vadra]], a businessman.\n*[[Varun Gandhi]] (1980), son of Sanjay Gandhi and Maneka Gandhi. He is a member of the [[Bharatiya Janata Party]], National Executive and the youngest National Secretary in the history of the party. He is a member of 2014 Lok Sabha, the lower house of Parliament of India, representing the Sultanpur constituency.<ref>http://www.firstpost.com/politics/5-facts-about-varun-gandhi-bjp-youngest-general-secretary-680086.html</ref> \n* Yamini Gandhi, wife of [[Varun Gandhi]].\n\n===Seventh generation===\n* Anasuya Gandhi (2020), daughter of [[Varun Gandhi]] and Yamini Gandhi.\n* Raihan Vadra and Miraya Vadra\u2014children of [[Priyanka Gandhi]] and [[Robert Vadra]].<ref>[http://www.indiatvnews.com/politics/national/rare-pictures-of-priyanka-and-robert-vadra-kids-9397.html?page=3 Priyanka kids]</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"100\">\nFile:Motilal nehru.jpg|[[Motilal Nehru]]\nFile:Jnehru.jpg|[[Jawaharlal Nehru]]\nFile:Kamala Nehru.jpg|[[Kamala Nehru]]\nFile:Vijaya Lakshmi Pandit.jpg|[[Vijaya Lakshmi Pandit]]\nFile:Krishna Nehru Hutheesing.jpg|[[Krishna Hutheesing]]\nFile:Indira Gandhi in 1967.jpg|[[Indira Gandhi]]\nFile:Rajiv Gandhi (1987).jpg|[[Rajiv Gandhi]]\nFile:Sanjay Gandhi cropped.jpg|[[Sanjay Gandhi]]\nFile:Sonia Gandhi (cropped).jpg|[[Sonia Gandhi]]\nFile:Maneka-Gandhi.jpg|[[Maneka Gandhi]]\nFile:Rahul Gandhi.jpg|[[Rahul Gandhi]]\nFile:Priyanka Gandhi in 2017.jpg|[[Priyanka Gandhi]]\nFile:Feroze Varun Gandhi 002.jpg|[[Varun Gandhi]]\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n\n*[[List of political families]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Nehru\u2013Gandhi family}}\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/world/gallery/2007/may/09/india?picture=329818381 The making of the Ghandhi dynasty] at [[The Guardian]]\n\n{{Indian National Congress}}\n\n{{Allahabad division topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nehru-Ghandy Family}}\n[[Category:Indian National Congress]]\n[[Category:People from Allahabad]]\n[[Category:Indian families]]\n[[Category:Parsi people]]\n[[Category:Hindu families]]\n[[Category:Political families of India]]\n[[Category:History of Allahabad]]\n", "name_user": "Kapaully", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(corrected wrongly written Mahatma Gandhi(incorrect) to M.K Gandhi(correct))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nehru%E2%80%93Gandhi_family"}
{"title_page": "Richard Catling", "text_new": "Sir '''Richard Charles Catling''' [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]], [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]], [[King's Police Medal for Gallantry|KPM]] (22 August 1912 &ndash; 22 March 2005) was a British police officer who rose to the rank of Commissioner of Police in Kenya from 1954 to 1963.<ref name=Times>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article380086.ece Sir Richard Catling], ''The Times'', 12 April 2005.</ref>\n\nCatling was previously an officer with the [[Palestine Police]] from 1935 until the British pulled out of the country in 1948, rising to the rank of assistant inspector-general of the CID in [[Jerusalem]].<ref name=Times/> After that, he went on to play a role in countering insurgencies in  Malaya and Kenya.<ref name=Telegraph>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1487117/Sir-Richard-Catling.html] ''The Daily Telegraph'' 05 Apr 2005</ref>\n__TOC__\n\n==Early life==\nCatling was born in [[Suffolk]] into a family of butchers and farmers. He attended grammar school in [[Bungay]], then joined a London textile company. Finding his job dull, he was on his way home by train one day in 1935, when he spotted an old friend standing on a station platform. His friend pointed out a poster calling for volunteers to join the Palestine Police. Catling crossed the platform and volunteered.<ref name=Times/>\n\n==Career==\n===Palestine===\nCatling joined the political branch of the CID in Jerusalem in 1936 and rose to the rank of assistant inspector-general CID in 1945, was awarded the Kings Police Medal, and held his post until the British withdrawal in 1948.<ref name=Times/>\n\n===Malaysia===\nHe then joined the Malay Police, helping deal with the communist insurgency and being awarded the OBE in 1951.<ref name=Times/> He took home leave in 1952 to marry Mary Joan Lewis (who predeceased him).\n\n===Kenya===\nIn 1954, he became Commissioner of Police in Kenya, during the [[Mau Mau]] rebellion. Shortly after his appointment, he visited [[Jomo Kenyatta]] in jail, hoping to understand the basis for [[Kikuyu people|Kikuyu]] discontent.  They got on well, and Kenyatta kept Catling on as Inspector-General of Police for a year after he came to power.<ref name=Times/> He was appointed CMG for his services to Kenya in 1956.\n\n===Retirement===\nHe was knighted on his retirement as Inspector-General of Police in 1964, and was made a Freeman of the City of London in 1979.<ref name=Times/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Catling, Richard}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n[[Category:British colonial police officers]]\n[[Category:Mandatory Palestine people of World War II]]\n", "text_old": "Sir '''Richard Charles Catling''' [[Companion of the Order of St Michael and St George|CMG]], [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]], [[King's Police Medal for Gallantry|KPM]] (22 August 1912 &ndash; 22 March 2005) was a British police officer who rose to the rank of Commissioner of Police in Kenya from 1954 to 1963.<ref name=Times>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article380086.ece Sir Richard Catling], ''The Times'', 12 April 2005.</ref>\n\nCatling was previously an officer with the [[Palestine Police]] from 1935 until the British pulled out of the country in 1948, rising to the rank of assistant inspector-general of the CID in [[Jerusalem]].<ref name=Times/> After that, he went on to play a role in countering insurgencies in  Malaya and Kenya.<ref name=Telegraph>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1487117/Sir-Richard-Catling.html] ''The Daily Telegraph'' 05 Apr 2005</ref>\n__TOC__\n\n==Early life==\nCatling was born in [[Suffolk]] into a family of butchers and farmers. He attended grammar school in [[Bungay]], then joined a London textile company. Finding his job dull, he was on his way home by train one day in 1935, when he spotted an old friend standing on a station platform. His friend pointed out a poster calling for volunteers to join the Palestine Police. Catling crossed the platform and volunteered.<ref name=Times/>\n\n==Career==\n===Palestine===\nCatling joined the political branch of the CID in Jerusalem in 1936 and rose to the rank of assistant inspector-general CID in 1945, was awarded the Kings Police Medal, and held his post until the British withdrawal in 1948.<ref name=Times/>\n\n===Malaysia===\nHe then joined the Malay Police, helping deal with the communist insurgency and being awarded the OBE in 1951.<ref name=Times/> He took home leave in 1952 to get married to Mary Joan Lewis (who predeceased him).\n\n===Kenya===\nIn 1954, he became Commissioner of Police in Kenya, during the [[Mau Mau]] rebellion. Shortly after his appointment, he visited [[Jomo Kenyatta]] in jail, hoping to understand the basis for [[Kikuyu people|Kikuyu]] discontent.  They got on well, and Kenyatta kept Catling on as Inspector-General of Police for a year after he came to power.<ref name=Times/> He was appointed CMG for his services to Kenya in 1956.\n\n===Retirement===\nHe was knighted on his retirement as Inspector-General of Police in 1964, and was made a Freeman of the City of London in 1979.<ref name=Times/>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Catling, Richard}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:2005 deaths]]\n[[Category:British colonial police officers]]\n[[Category:Mandatory Palestine people of World War II]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Catling"}
{"title_page": "Kumay River", "text_new": "{{Infobox river\n  | name              = Kumay River\n  | image             = \n  | image_size        = \n  | image_alt         =\n  | image_caption     = \n  | map               = \n  | map_size          = \n  | map_alt           =\n  | map_caption       = \n  | source1_location  = \n  | mouth_location    = [[Kolva River (Perm Krai)|Kolva River]]\n  | subdivision_type1 = Country\n  | subdivision_name1 = [[Russia]]\n  | progression       = {{RKolva}}\n  | length            = {{convert|23|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n  | source1_elevation = \n  | mouth_elevation   = \n  | discharge1_avg    = \n  | basin_size        = \n  | river_system      = \n  | tributaries_left  =\n  | tributaries_right =\n}}\n\nThe '''Kumay''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u0443\u043c\u0430\u0439}}) is a river in [[Perm Krai]], [[Russia]], a left [[tributary]] of the [[Kolva River (Perm Krai)|Kolva River]], which in turn is a tributary of the [[Vishera River (Perm Krai)|Vishera River]]. The length of the river is {{convert|23|km|sp=us}}. It flows into the Kolva River at the point located {{convert|326|km|sp=us}} away from the Kolva's mouth.<ref name='\u041c\u041f\u0420 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438'>{{cite web|url=http://textual.ru/gvr/index.php?card=180481|title=\u0413\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0440 \u0420\u0424: \u041a\u0443\u043c\u0430\u0439}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Perm Krai}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Russia}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Perm Krai]]\n\n\n{{PermKrai-geo-stub}}\n{{Russia-river-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox river\n  | name              = Kumay River\n  | image             = \n  | image_size        = \n  | image_alt         =\n  | image_caption     = \n  | map               = \n  | map_size          = \n  | map_alt           =\n  | map_caption       = \n  | source1_location  = \n  | mouth_location    = [[Kolva River (Perm Krai)|Kolva River]]\n  | subdivision_type1 = Country\n  | subdivision_name1 = [[Russia]]\n  | progression       = \n  | length            = {{convert|23|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n  | source1_elevation = \n  | mouth_elevation   = \n  | discharge1_avg    = \n  | basin_size        = \n  | river_system      = \n  | tributaries_left  =\n  | tributaries_right =\n}}\n\nThe '''Kumay''' ({{lang-ru|\u041a\u0443\u043c\u0430\u0439}}) is a river in [[Perm Krai]], [[Russia]], a left [[tributary]] of the [[Kolva River (Perm Krai)|Kolva River]], which in turn is a tributary of the [[Vishera River (Perm Krai)|Vishera River]]. The length of the river is {{convert|23|km|sp=us}}. It flows into the Kolva River at the point located {{convert|326|km|sp=us}} away from the Kolva's mouth.<ref name='\u041c\u041f\u0420 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438'>{{cite web|url=http://textual.ru/gvr/index.php?card=180481|title=\u0413\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0440 \u0420\u0424: \u041a\u0443\u043c\u0430\u0439}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Perm Krai}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Russia}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Perm Krai]]\n\n\n{{PermKrai-geo-stub}}\n{{Russia-river-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "progression", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kumay_River"}
{"title_page": "They Came to a City (play)", "text_new": "{{Infobox play\n| name              = They Came to a City \n| image             = \n| image_size        =\n| caption           =\n| writer            = [[J.B. Priestley]]\n| setting           = \n| date of premiere  = 25 January 1943\n| original language = English\n| place             =Princes Theatre, [[Bradford]]\n| series            = \n| subject           = \n| genre             = Drama\n}}\n'''''They Came to a City''''' is a 1943 play by the British writer [[J.B. Priestley]].\n\nAfter premiering at the Princes Theatre, [[Bradford]] it transferred to the [[Gielgud Theatre|Globe Theatre]] in [[London]]'s [[West End theatre|West End]]. It ran for 280 performances between 21 April and 11 December 1943. The cast included [[John Clements (actor)|John Clements]], [[Googie Withers]], [[Raymond Huntley]], [[A.E. Matthews]] and [[Renee Gadd]].<ref>Wearing p.110</ref> \n\n==Adaptation==\nIn 1944 it was [[They Came to a City|made into a film]] by [[Ealing Studios]], directed by [[Basil Dearden]] and with the cast all reprising their roles.<ref>Goble p.376</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Goble, Alan. ''The Complete Index to Literary Sources in Film''. Walter de Gruyter, 1999.\n* Wearing, J.P. ''The London Stage 1940-1949: A Calendar of Productions, Performers, and Personnel''.  Rowman & Littlefield, 2014.\n\n{{JBPriestley}}\n\n[[Category:1943 plays]]\n[[Category:Plays by J. B. Priestley]]\n[[Category:British plays]]\n[[Category:British plays adapted into films]]\n[[Category:West End plays]]\n\n{{1940s-play-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox play\n| name              = They Came to a City \n| image             = \n| image_size        =\n| caption           =\n| writer            = [[J.B. Priestley]]\n| setting           = \n| date of premiere  = 25 January 1943\n| original language = English\n| place             =Princes Theatre, [[Bradford]]\n| series            = \n| subject           = \n| genre             = Drama\n}}\n'''''They Came to a City''''' is a 1943 play by the British writer [[J.B. Priestley]].\n\nAfter premiering at the Princes Theatre, [[Bradford]] it transferred to the [[Gielgud Theatre|Globe Theatre]] in [[London]]'s [[West End theatre|West End]]. It ran for 280 performances between 21 April and 11 December 1943. The cast included [[John Clements]], [[Googie Withers]], [[Raymond Huntley]], [[A.E. Matthews]] and [[Renee Gadd]].<ref>Wearing p.110</ref> \n\n==Adaptation==\nIn 1944 it was [[They Came to a City|made into a film]] by [[Ealing Studios]], directed by [[Basil Dearden]] and with the cast all reprising their roles.<ref>Goble p.376</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* Goble, Alan. ''The Complete Index to Literary Sources in Film''. Walter de Gruyter, 1999.\n* Wearing, J.P. ''The London Stage 1940-1949: A Calendar of Productions, Performers, and Personnel''.  Rowman & Littlefield, 2014.\n\n{{JBPriestley}}\n\n[[Category:1943 plays]]\n[[Category:Plays by J. B. Priestley]]\n[[Category:British plays]]\n[[Category:British plays adapted into films]]\n[[Category:West End plays]]\n\n{{1940s-play-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toJohn Clements(link changed toJohn Clements (actor)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/They_Came_to_a_City_(play)"}
{"title_page": "Sherwood B. Idso", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Sherwood Idso\n| image             =\n| image_size        = 200px\n| birth_date        = {{Birth-date and age|June 12, 1942}}\n| birth_place       = [[Thief River Falls, Minnesota]]\n| residence         = [[United States]]\n| nationality       = American\n| fields            = [[Climatology]], [[Ecology]], [[Soil Science]]\n| workplaces        = [[University of Minnesota]],<br>[[United States Department of Agriculture|U.S. Department of Agriculture]],<br>[[Center for the Study of Carbon Dioxide and Global Change]]\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Minnesota]]\n| thesis_title      = The photosynthetic response of plants to their environment: a holocoenotic method of analysis\n| thesis_url        = http://www.worldcat.org/title/photosynthetic-response-of-plants-to-their-environment-a-holocoenotic-method-of-analysis/oclc/62428704\n| thesis_year       = 1967\n| awards            = [[Arthur S. Flemming Award]] (1977), [[Petr Beckmann]] Award (2003)\n}}\n\n'''Sherwood B. Idso''' (born June 12, 1942)<ref name=kirkham>{{cite book |title=Principles of Soil and Plant Water Relations |last=Kirkham |first=M.B. |year=2005 |publisher=[[Academic Press]] |isbn=978-0124097513 |page=451 |accessdate=2012-08-18 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y5r8AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA497}}</ref> is the president of the [[Center for the Study of Carbon Dioxide and Global Change]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.co2science.org/about/president.php|title=President|publisher=CO2 Science}}</ref> a [[501(c)(3)]] [[nonprofit organization|nonprofit]] that disputes the consensus [[scientific opinion on climate change]]. Previously he was a Research Physicist with the [[U.S. Department of Agriculture]]'s [[Agricultural Research Service]] at the U.S. Water Conservation Laboratory in Phoenix, Arizona, where he worked since June 1967. He was also closely associated with [[Arizona State University]] over most of this period, serving as an Adjunct Professor in the Departments of Geology, Geography, and Botany and Microbiology. His two sons, [[Craig Idso|Craig]] and [[Keith Idso|Keith]], are, respectively, the founder<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.motherjones.com/environment/2009/12/dirty-dozen-climate-change-denial-11-idso-family%20%20 | title=No. 8: Center for the Study of Carbon Dioxide and Global Change (A.K.A. The Idso Family) | work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]] | date=4 December 2009 | accessdate=15 March 2014 | author=Harkinson, Josh}}</ref> and vice president<ref>[http://www.co2science.org/about/vice_president.php Vice President], CO2Science</ref> of the Center for the Study of Carbon Dioxide and Global Change.\n\nIdso is the author or co-author of over 500 publications including the books Carbon Dioxide: Friend or Foe? (1982) and Carbon Dioxide and Global Change: Earth in Transition (1989). He served on the editorial board of the international journal Agricultural and Forest Meteorology from 1973 to 1993 and since 1993 has served on the editorial board of Environmental and Experimental Botany.  Over the course of his career, he has been an invited reviewer of manuscripts for 56 different scientific journals and 17 different funding agencies, representing an unusually large array of disciplines. He is an [[ISI highly cited researcher]].<ref name=ISI>{{cite web |url=http://highlycited.com/names/I.html |title=ISI Highly Cited: Sherwood B. Idso |publisher=[[Institute for Scientific Information]] |accessdate=July 23, 2010}}</ref><ref name=isiarchive>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929111210/http://hcr3.isiknowledge.com/author.cgi?&link1=Browse&link2=Results&id=1340 | archivedate=September 29, 2007 | title=Idso, Sherwood B. | publisher=ISI HighlyCited.com| url=http://hcr3.isiknowledge.com/author.cgi?&link1=Browse&link2=Results&id=1340}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nSherwood Idso was born in [[Thief River Falls, Minnesota]] on June 12, 1942, where he lived until graduating from high school in 1960.<ref name=kirkham/> Idso then attended the [[University of Minnesota College of Science and Engineering|Institute of Technology]] at the [[University of Minnesota]], receiving a B.Phys. in Physics with distinction in 1964, followed by an M.S. in Soil Science (with a minor in Physics) in 1966 and then a Ph.D. in Soil Science (with a minor in Meteorology and Mechanical Engineering) in 1968.<ref name=kirkham/><ref name=isiarchive/> His doctoral thesis was titled, ''The photosynthetic response of plants to their environment: a holocoenotic method of analysis''.<ref>{{cite journal | author=Idso, Sherwood B. | title=The photosynthetic response of plants to their environment: a holocoenotic method of analysis | publisher=[[University of Minnesota]] | year=1967| oclc=62428704 }}</ref>\n\n==Climate science==\nIn 1972, Idso published an article called \"An American [[Haboob]]\", in which he documented a large dust storm in Arizona which occurred on July 16, 1971, and which stretched from [[Tucson]] to [[Phoenix, AZ|Phoenix]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Idso|first=S. B.|author2=Ingram, R. S. |author3=Pritchard, J. M. |title=An American Haboob|journal=Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society|date=October 1972|volume=53|issue=10|pages=930\u2013935|doi=10.1175/1520-0477(1972)053<0930:AAH>2.0.CO;2|bibcode=1972BAMS...53..930I|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.azfamily.com/weather/An-American-Haboob--Part-3-121671484.html | title=An American Haboob Part 3 | work=[[Azfamily.com]] | date=11 May 2011 | accessdate=17 April 2014 | author=Norman, Royal | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419014733/http://www.azfamily.com/weather/An-American-Haboob--Part-3-121671484.html | archivedate=19 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1980, Idso published research which concluded that [[climate sensitivity]] was probably only about 0.3&nbsp;\u00b0C.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Idso|first=S. B.|title=The Climatological Significance of a Doubling of Earth's Atmospheric Carbon Dioxide Concentration|journal=Science|date=28 March 1980|volume=207|issue=4438|pages=1462\u20131463|doi=10.1126/science.207.4438.1462|pmid=17779615|bibcode=1980Sci...207.1462I}}</ref> The following year, he criticized [[NASA]]'s global warming predictions, saying they were \"about 10 times too great,\" adding that, in his view, global warming would have a beneficial effect on agriculture.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.csmonitor.com/1981/1202/120228.html/(page)/2 | title=Is the world getting warmer? | work=[[Christian Science Monitor]] | date=2 December 1981 | accessdate=25 March 2014 | author=Starr, Douglas}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, Idso, along with A.J. Brazel, published a study in ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' which concluded, contrary to a report the [[National Academy of Sciences]] released the previous year, that rising CO<sub>2</sub> levels would increase [[streamflow]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Idso|first=S. B.|author2=Brazel, A. J. |title=Rising atmospheric carbon dioxide concentrations may increase streamflow|journal=Nature|date=1 November 1984|volume=312|issue=5989|pages=51\u201353|doi=10.1038/312051a0|url=https://naldc-legacy.nal.usda.gov/naldc/download.xhtml?id=50585&content=PDF|bibcode=1984Natur.312...51I}}</ref> The study's authors argued that the NAS report came to the opposite conclusion because it neglected the effect of rising CO<sub>2</sub> levels on plants.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.csmonitor.com/1984/1213/121323.html/(page)/2 | title=New CO[2] data undercuts dire prediction icecaps would melt. Chillier winters, hungrier bugs ahead? | work=Christian Science Monitor | date=13 December 1984 | accessdate=27 March 2014 | author=Cowen, Robert C.}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1997 book, ''Global Warming: The Science and the Politics'' Idso said: \"I find no compelling reason to believe that the earth will necessarily experience any global warming as a consequence of the ongoing rise in the atmosphere's carbon dioxide concentration.\"<ref>{{cite book | author=Jones, Laura | year=1997 | url=https://archive.org/details/globalwarmingsci0000unse | url-status=dead | title=Global Warming: The Science and the Politics | publisher=[[Fraser Institute]] | isbn=978-0889751842 | url-access=registration }}</ref>\n\nIn the 1998 paper, ''CO2-induced global warming: a skeptic's view of potential climate change'' Idso said: \"Several of these cooling forces have individually been estimated to be of equivalent magnitude, but of opposite sign, to the typically predicted [[greenhouse effect]] of a doubling of the air\u2019s CO2 content, which suggests to me that little net temperature change will ultimately result from the ongoing buildup of CO2 in Earth's atmosphere.\"<ref>{{Cite journal | first1=Sherwood B. | last1=Idso | title=CO2-induced global warming: a skeptic's view of potential climate change | journal=[[Climate Research (journal)|Climate Research]] | year=1998 | volume=10 | issue=1 | pages=69\u201382 | doi=10.3354/cr010069| bibcode=1998ClRes..10...69I | doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* 1977 - [[Arthur S. Flemming Award]] in recognition of \"his innovative research into fundamental aspects of agricultural-climatological interrelationships affecting food production and the identification of achievable research goals whose attainment could significantly aid in assessment and improvement of world food supplies.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://flemming.gwu.edu/past-recipients-2/ | title=Arthur S. Fleming Award Recipients, 1948-2005 | publisher=[[George Washington University]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | author=Kirkham, M.B. | year=2005 | url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/book/9780124097513 | title=Principles of Soil and Plant Water Relations | publisher=[[Academic Press]]}}</ref>\n* 2003 - [[Doctors for Disaster Preparedness#Petr Beckmann Award|Petr Beckmann Award]] for \"courage and achievement in defense of scientific truth and freedom.\"<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.ddponline.org/ddpnews/ddpjul03.htm | title=Doctors for Disaster Preparedness Newsletter | date=July 2003 | publisher=[[Doctors for Disaster Preparedness]]}}</ref>\n* 2014 - [[Frederick Seitz]] Memorial Award (presented by [[Heartland Institute]])\n\n==Selected publications==\n* {{cite journal\n  | first1=Sherwood B. | last1=Idso\n  | title=The Climatological Significance of a Doubling of Earth's Atmospheric Carbon Dioxide Concentration\n  | journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]]\n  | year=1980 | volume=207 | issue=4438 | pages=1462\u20131463\n  | doi=10.1126/science.207.4438.1462 | pmid=17779615\n  | bibcode=1980Sci...207.1462I}}\n* {{cite journal\n  | first1=S. B. | last1=Idso\n  | first2=A. J. | last2=Brazel\n  | title=Rising atmospheric carbon dioxide concentrations may increase streamflow\n  | journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]\n  | year=1984 | volume=312 | issue=5989 | pages=51\u201353\n  | doi=10.1038/312051a0\n  | bibcode=1984Natur.312...51I}}\n* {{cite journal\n  | first1=S. B. | last1=Idso\n  | title=Greenhouse warming or Little Ice Age demise: A critical problem for climatology\n  | journal=Theoretical and Applied Climatology\n  | year=1988 | volume=39 | issue=1 | pages=54\u201356\n  | doi=10.1007/BF00867657 | bibcode=1988ThApC..39...54I\n  | url=https://zenodo.org/record/1232462\n }}\n* {{cite journal\n  | first1=Keith E.    | last1=Idso\n  | first2=Sherwood B. | last2=Idso\n  | title=Plant responses to atmospheric CO2 enrichment in the face of environmental constraints: a review of the past 10 years' research\n  | journal=[[Agricultural and Forest Meteorology]]\n  | year=1994 | volume=64 | issue=3\u20134 | pages=153\u2013203\n  | doi=10.1016/0168-1923(94)90025-6\n  | bibcode=1994AgFM...69..153I}}\n* {{cite journal \n  | first1=Sherwood B. | last1=Idso \n  | title=CO2-induced global warming: a skeptic's view of potential climate change \n  | journal=[[Climate Research (journal)|Climate Research]] \n  | year=1998 | volume=10 | issue=1 | pages=69\u201382 \n  | doi=10.3354/cr010069\n| bibcode=1998ClRes..10...69I| url=https://zenodo.org/record/1000718| doi-access=free}}\n* {{cite journal \n  | first1=Bruce A.    | last1=Kimball\n  | first2=Sherwood B. | last2=Idso\n  | first3=Stephanie   | last3=Johnson\n  | first4=Matthias C. | last4=Rillig\n  | title=Seventeen years of carbon dioxide enrichment of sour orange trees: final results \n  | journal=Global Change Biology\n  | year=2007 | volume=13 | issue=10 | pages=2171\u20132183\n  | doi=10.1111/j.1365-2486.2007.01430.x\n| bibcode=2007GCBio..13.2171K}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.co2science.org/ CO2 Science]\n* {{YouTube|LPNiBVU2QIA|Sherwood Idso - Carbon Dioxide: The Breath of Life}}\n* {{YouTube|59GWEJa6DHo|Sherwood Idso - 15 Years Enriching Trees with CO2: An Update on Sherwood's Forest}}, [[Doctors for Disaster Preparedness]] Meeting, July 12, 2003\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Idso, Sherwood}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Minnesota alumni]]\n[[Category:American climatologists]]\n[[Category:Highly Cited Researchers]]\n[[Category:People from Thief River Falls, Minnesota]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n| name              = Sherwood Idso\n| image             =\n| image_size        = 200px\n| birth_date        = {{Birth-date and age|June 12, 1942}}\n| birth_place       = [[Thief River Falls, Minnesota]]\n| residence         = [[United States]]\n| nationality       = American\n| fields            = [[Climatology]], [[Ecology]], [[Soil Science]]\n| workplaces        = [[University of Minnesota]],<br>[[United States Department of Agriculture|U.S. Department of Agriculture]],<br>[[Center for the Study of Carbon Dioxide and Global Change]]\n| alma_mater        = [[University of Minnesota]]\n| thesis_title      = The photosynthetic response of plants to their environment: a holocoenotic method of analysis\n| thesis_url        = http://www.worldcat.org/title/photosynthetic-response-of-plants-to-their-environment-a-holocoenotic-method-of-analysis/oclc/62428704\n| thesis_year       = 1967\n| awards            = [[Arthur S. Flemming Award]] (1977), [[Petr Beckmann]] Award (2003)\n}}\n\n'''Sherwood B. Idso''' (born June 12, 1942)<ref name=kirkham>{{cite book |title=Principles of Soil and Plant Water Relations |last=Kirkham |first=M.B. |year=2005 |publisher=[[Academic Press]] |isbn=978-0124097513 |page=451 |accessdate=2012-08-18 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Y5r8AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA497}}</ref> is the president of the [[Center for the Study of Carbon Dioxide and Global Change]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.co2science.org/about/president.php|title=President|publisher=CO2 Science}}</ref> a [[501(c)(3)]] [[nonprofit organization|nonprofit]] that disputes the consensus [[scientific opinion on climate change]]. Previously he was a Research Physicist with the [[U.S. Department of Agriculture]]'s [[Agricultural Research Service]] at the U.S. Water Conservation Laboratory in Phoenix, Arizona, where he worked since June 1967. He was also closely associated with [[Arizona State University]] over most of this period, serving as an Adjunct Professor in the Departments of Geology, Geography, and Botany and Microbiology. His two sons, [[Craig Idso|Craig]] and [[Keith Idso|Keith]], are, respectively, the founder<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.motherjones.com/environment/2009/12/dirty-dozen-climate-change-denial-11-idso-family%20%20 | title=No. 8: Center for the Study of Carbon Dioxide and Global Change (A.K.A. The Idso Family) | work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]] | date=4 December 2009 | accessdate=15 March 2014 | author=Harkinson, Josh}}</ref> and vice president<ref>[http://www.co2science.org/about/vice_president.php Vice President], CO2Science</ref> of the Center for the Study of Carbon Dioxide and Global Change.\n\nIdso is the author or co-author of over 500 publications including the books Carbon Dioxide: Friend or Foe? (1982) and Carbon Dioxide and Global Change: Earth in Transition (1989). He served on the editorial board of the international journal Agricultural and Forest Meteorology from 1973 to 1993 and since 1993 has served on the editorial board of Environmental and Experimental Botany.  Over the course of his career, he has been an invited reviewer of manuscripts for 56 different scientific journals and 17 different funding agencies, representing an unusually large array of disciplines. He is an [[ISI highly cited researcher]].<ref name=ISI>{{cite web |url=http://highlycited.com/names/I.html |title=ISI Highly Cited: Sherwood B. Idso |publisher=[[Institute for Scientific Information]] |accessdate=July 23, 2010}}</ref><ref name=isiarchive>{{cite web | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929111210/http://hcr3.isiknowledge.com/author.cgi?&link1=Browse&link2=Results&id=1340 | archivedate=September 29, 2007 | title=Idso, Sherwood B. | publisher=ISI HighlyCited.com| url=http://hcr3.isiknowledge.com/author.cgi?&link1=Browse&link2=Results&id=1340}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nSherwood Idso was born in [[Thief River Falls, Minnesota]] on June 12, 1942, where he lived until graduating from high school in 1960.<ref name=kirkham/> Idso then attended the [[University of Minnesota College of Science and Engineering|Institute of Technology]] at the [[University of Minnesota]], receiving a B.Phys. in Physics with distinction in 1964, followed by an M.S. in Soil Science (with a minor in Physics) in 1966 and then a Ph.D. in Soil Science (with a minor in Meteorology and Mechanical Engineering) in 1968.<ref name=kirkham/><ref name=isiarchive/> His doctoral thesis was titled, ''The photosynthetic response of plants to their environment: a holocoenotic method of analysis''.<ref>{{cite journal | author=Idso, Sherwood B. | title=The photosynthetic response of plants to their environment: a holocoenotic method of analysis | publisher=[[University of Minnesota]] | year=1967| oclc=62428704 }}</ref>\n\n==Climate science==\nIn 1972, Idso published an article called \"An American [[Haboob]]\", in which he documented a large dust storm in Arizona which occurred on July 16, 1971, and which stretched from [[Tucson]] to [[Phoenix, AZ|Phoenix]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Idso|first=S. B.|author2=Ingram, R. S. |author3=Pritchard, J. M. |title=An American Haboob|journal=Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society|date=October 1972|volume=53|issue=10|pages=930\u2013935|doi=10.1175/1520-0477(1972)053<0930:AAH>2.0.CO;2|bibcode=1972BAMS...53..930I|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.azfamily.com/weather/An-American-Haboob--Part-3-121671484.html | title=An American Haboob Part 3 | work=[[Azfamily.com]] | date=11 May 2011 | accessdate=17 April 2014 | author=Norman, Royal | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140419014733/http://www.azfamily.com/weather/An-American-Haboob--Part-3-121671484.html | archivedate=19 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1980, Idso published research which concluded that [[climate sensitivity]] was probably only about 0.3&nbsp;\u00b0C.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Idso|first=S. B.|title=The Climatological Significance of a Doubling of Earth's Atmospheric Carbon Dioxide Concentration|journal=Science|date=28 March 1980|volume=207|issue=4438|pages=1462\u20131463|doi=10.1126/science.207.4438.1462|pmid=17779615|bibcode=1980Sci...207.1462I}}</ref> The following year, he criticized [[NASA]]'s global warming predictions, saying they were \"about 10 times too great,\" adding that, in his view, global warming would have a beneficial effect on agriculture.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.csmonitor.com/1981/1202/120228.html/(page)/2 | title=Is the world getting warmer? | work=[[Christian Science Monitor]] | date=2 December 1981 | accessdate=25 March 2014 | author=Starr, Douglas}}</ref>\n\nIn 1984, Idso, along with A.J. Brazel, published a study in ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]'' which concluded, contrary to a report the [[National Academy of Sciences]] released the previous year, that rising CO<sub>2</sub> levels would increase [[streamflow]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Idso|first=S. B.|author2=Brazel, A. J. |title=Rising atmospheric carbon dioxide concentrations may increase streamflow|journal=Nature|date=1 November 1984|volume=312|issue=5989|pages=51\u201353|doi=10.1038/312051a0|url=https://naldc-legacy.nal.usda.gov/naldc/download.xhtml?id=50585&content=PDF|bibcode=1984Natur.312...51I}}</ref> The study's authors argued that the NAS report came to the opposite conclusion because it neglected the effect of rising CO<sub>2</sub> levels on plants.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.csmonitor.com/1984/1213/121323.html/(page)/2 | title=New CO[2] data undercuts dire prediction icecaps would melt. Chillier winters, hungrier bugs ahead? | work=Christian Science Monitor | date=13 December 1984 | accessdate=27 March 2014 | author=Cowen, Robert C.}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1997 book, ''Global Warming: The Science and the Politics'' Idso said: \"I find no compelling reason to believe that the earth will necessarily experience any global warming as a consequence of the ongoing rise in the atmosphere's carbon dioxide concentration.\"<ref>{{cite book | author=Jones, Laura | year=1997 | url=https://archive.org/details/globalwarmingsci0000unse | url-status=dead | title=Global Warming: The Science and the Politics | publisher=[[Fraser Institute]] | isbn=978-0889751842 | url-access=registration }}</ref>\n\nIn the 1998 paper, ''CO2-induced global warming: a skeptic's view of potential climate change'' Idso said: \"Several of these cooling forces have individually been estimated to be of equivalent magnitude, but of opposite sign, to the typically predicted greenhouse effect of a doubling of the air\u2019s CO2 content, which suggests to me that little net temperature change will ultimately result from the ongoing buildup of CO2 in Earth's atmosphere.\"<ref>{{Cite journal | first1=Sherwood B. | last1=Idso | title=CO2-induced global warming: a skeptic's view of potential climate change | journal=[[Climate Research (journal)|Climate Research]] | year=1998 | volume=10 | issue=1 | pages=69\u201382 | doi=10.3354/cr010069| bibcode=1998ClRes..10...69I | doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* 1977 - [[Arthur S. Flemming Award]] in recognition of \"his innovative research into fundamental aspects of agricultural-climatological interrelationships affecting food production and the identification of achievable research goals whose attainment could significantly aid in assessment and improvement of world food supplies.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://flemming.gwu.edu/past-recipients-2/ | title=Arthur S. Fleming Award Recipients, 1948-2005 | publisher=[[George Washington University]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | author=Kirkham, M.B. | year=2005 | url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/book/9780124097513 | title=Principles of Soil and Plant Water Relations | publisher=[[Academic Press]]}}</ref>\n* 2003 - [[Doctors for Disaster Preparedness#Petr Beckmann Award|Petr Beckmann Award]] for \"courage and achievement in defense of scientific truth and freedom.\"<ref>{{cite journal | url=http://www.ddponline.org/ddpnews/ddpjul03.htm | title=Doctors for Disaster Preparedness Newsletter | date=July 2003 | publisher=[[Doctors for Disaster Preparedness]]}}</ref>\n* 2014 - [[Frederick Seitz]] Memorial Award (presented by [[Heartland Institute]])\n\n==Selected publications==\n* {{cite journal\n  | first1=Sherwood B. | last1=Idso\n  | title=The Climatological Significance of a Doubling of Earth's Atmospheric Carbon Dioxide Concentration\n  | journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]]\n  | year=1980 | volume=207 | issue=4438 | pages=1462\u20131463\n  | doi=10.1126/science.207.4438.1462 | pmid=17779615\n  | bibcode=1980Sci...207.1462I}}\n* {{cite journal\n  | first1=S. B. | last1=Idso\n  | first2=A. J. | last2=Brazel\n  | title=Rising atmospheric carbon dioxide concentrations may increase streamflow\n  | journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]\n  | year=1984 | volume=312 | issue=5989 | pages=51\u201353\n  | doi=10.1038/312051a0\n  | bibcode=1984Natur.312...51I}}\n* {{cite journal\n  | first1=S. B. | last1=Idso\n  | title=Greenhouse warming or Little Ice Age demise: A critical problem for climatology\n  | journal=Theoretical and Applied Climatology\n  | year=1988 | volume=39 | issue=1 | pages=54\u201356\n  | doi=10.1007/BF00867657 | bibcode=1988ThApC..39...54I\n  | url=https://zenodo.org/record/1232462\n }}\n* {{cite journal\n  | first1=Keith E.    | last1=Idso\n  | first2=Sherwood B. | last2=Idso\n  | title=Plant responses to atmospheric CO2 enrichment in the face of environmental constraints: a review of the past 10 years' research\n  | journal=[[Agricultural and Forest Meteorology]]\n  | year=1994 | volume=64 | issue=3\u20134 | pages=153\u2013203\n  | doi=10.1016/0168-1923(94)90025-6\n  | bibcode=1994AgFM...69..153I}}\n* {{cite journal \n  | first1=Sherwood B. | last1=Idso \n  | title=CO2-induced global warming: a skeptic's view of potential climate change \n  | journal=[[Climate Research (journal)|Climate Research]] \n  | year=1998 | volume=10 | issue=1 | pages=69\u201382 \n  | doi=10.3354/cr010069\n| bibcode=1998ClRes..10...69I| url=https://zenodo.org/record/1000718| doi-access=free}}\n* {{cite journal \n  | first1=Bruce A.    | last1=Kimball\n  | first2=Sherwood B. | last2=Idso\n  | first3=Stephanie   | last3=Johnson\n  | first4=Matthias C. | last4=Rillig\n  | title=Seventeen years of carbon dioxide enrichment of sour orange trees: final results \n  | journal=Global Change Biology\n  | year=2007 | volume=13 | issue=10 | pages=2171\u20132183\n  | doi=10.1111/j.1365-2486.2007.01430.x\n| bibcode=2007GCBio..13.2171K}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.co2science.org/ CO2 Science]\n* {{YouTube|LPNiBVU2QIA|Sherwood Idso - Carbon Dioxide: The Breath of Life}}\n* {{YouTube|59GWEJa6DHo|Sherwood Idso - 15 Years Enriching Trees with CO2: An Update on Sherwood's Forest}}, [[Doctors for Disaster Preparedness]] Meeting, July 12, 2003\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Idso, Sherwood}}\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Minnesota alumni]]\n[[Category:American climatologists]]\n[[Category:Highly Cited Researchers]]\n[[Category:People from Thief River Falls, Minnesota]]\n", "name_user": "Kku", "label": "safe", "comment": "linkgreenhouse effectusingFind link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sherwood_B._Idso"}
{"title_page": "University of Computer Studies (Maubin)", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n| name = University of Computer Studies (Maubin)\n| native_name = \u1000\u103d\u1014\u103a\u1015\u103b\u1030\u1010\u102c\u1010\u1000\u1039\u1000\u101e\u102d\u102f\u101c\u103a(\u1019\u1021\u1030\u1015\u1004\u103a)\n| native_name_lang = my\n| former_name = Computer College (Maubin)\n| motto = \u1019\u103c\u1014\u103a\u1019\u103e\u1014\u103a\u1010\u103d\u1000\u103a\u1001\u103b\u1000\u103a \u1010\u102d\u102f\u1004\u103a\u1038\u1015\u103c\u100a\u103a\u1010\u103d\u1000\u103a\n| motto_lang = my\n| established = {{start date and age|2003}}\n| type = Public\n| affiliation = [[Ministry of Education (Science and Technology)]]\n| rector = Professor Dr. Thandar Thein\n| address = Between Block 1 and Block 2, Sein Mya Kan Thar Road\n| city = [[Ma-ubin|Maubin]]\n| state = [[Ayeyarwaddy|Ayeyarwaddy Region]]\n| country = [[Myanmar]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|16|44|28.1|N|95|39|05.1|E|type:edu|display=inline}}\n| colours = [[Turquoise]]   {{color box|turquoise}}\n| website = https://ucsmub.edu.mm/\n| logo = UCSMUB Logo.png\n}}\n\n'''University of Computer Studies (Maubin)''' ({{Lang-my|\u1000\u103d\u1014\u103a\u1015\u103b\u1030\u1010\u102c\u1010\u1000\u1039\u1000\u101e\u102d\u102f\u101c\u103a(\u1019\u1021\u1030\u1015\u1004\u103a)}} {{IPA-my|k\u028a\u0300\u0270\u0303pj\u00f9t\u00e0 t\u025b\u0294k\u0259\u03b8\u00f2 (m\u0259\u0294\u00f9b\u026a\u0300\u0270\u0303)}}) is situated on Seinmya Kanthar Street between No. (1) ward and No. (2) ward in [[Ma-ubin|Maubin]], [[Ma-ubin District|Maubin district]], [[Ayeyarwady Region|Ayeyarwaddy Region]], [[Myanmar]]. It extends as far as 42.552 acres.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://ucsmbn.moe.edu.mm/?page_id=8|title=BackGround History \u00bb Computer University (Maubin)|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n'''Government Computer College (Maubin)''' started up on first January 2003. It was upgraded as '''Computer University (Maubin)''' on 20<sup>th</sup> January 2007.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Citation|title=\u1000\u103d\u1014\u103a\u1015\u103b\u1030\u1010\u102c\u1010\u1000\u1039\u1000\u101e\u102d\u102f\u101c\u103a(\u1019\u1021\u1030\u1015\u1004\u103a)|date=2019-06-05|url=https://my.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=%E1%80%80%E1%80%BD%E1%80%94%E1%80%BA%E1%80%95%E1%80%BB%E1%80%B0%E1%80%90%E1%80%AC%E1%80%90%E1%80%80%E1%80%B9%E1%80%80%E1%80%9E%E1%80%AD%E1%80%AF%E1%80%9C%E1%80%BA(%E1%80%99%E1%80%A1%E1%80%B0%E1%80%95%E1%80%84%E1%80%BA)&oldid=461891|work=\u101d\u102e\u1000\u102e\u1015\u102e\u1038\u1012\u102e\u1038\u101a\u102c\u1038|language=my|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref> In 2015, It was renamed as '''University of Computer Studies (Maubin)'''.\n\n== Bachelor Degree ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Degree Programmes\n!No\n!Name\n!Type\n!Duration\n|-\n|1\n|B.C.Sc (Bachelor of Computer Science)\n|Bachelor\n|5 Years\n|-\n|2\n|B.C.Tech (Bachelor of Computer Technology)\n|Bachelor\n|5 Years\n|-\n|3\n|D.C.Sc. (Diploma in Computer Science)\n|Post Graduate\n|1 Year\n|}\n\n== Faculty ==\n\n=== '''Academic Faculties'''\u200b ===\n\n# Faculty of Computer Science\n# Faculty of Information Science\n# Faculty of Computing\n# Faculty of Computer System and Technology\n# Faculty of Natural Science\n# Faculty of Languages\n#* Department of Myanmar\n#* Department of English\n# Department of Information Technology Supporting and Maintenance\n#* Department of Application\n\n=== '''Management Departments''' ===\n\n# Staff Affair Department\n# Student Affair Department\n# Finance Department\n# Estate Department\n\n== Rectors/Principals ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Rectors/Principals of UCSMUB\n!No\n!Name\n!Role\n!Active (MM/YYY)\n|-\n|1\n|Daw Moe Moe Win\n|Principal\n|01/2003 - 11/2003\n|-\n|2\n|Dr. Tar Khin\n|Principal\n|11/2003 - 09/2004\n|-\n|3\n|Dr. Mie Mie Su Thwin\n|Principal\n|09/2004 - 10/2005\n|-\n|4\n|Dr. Thin Thin Htike\n|Principal\n|10/2005 - 05/2006\n|-\n|5\n|Dr. Hla Myat Kaung\n|Principal\n|05/2006 - 07/2008\n|-\n|6\n|Dr. Hinn Min Oo\n|Principal\n|08/2008 - 07/2010\n|-\n|7\n|Dr. Thae Nu Phyu\n|Principal\n|07/2010 - 01/2013\n|-\n|8\n|Dr. Khaing Khaing Oo\n|Principal\n|01/2013 - 04/2015\n|-\n|9\n|Dr. Thandar Thein\n|Rector\n|02/2015 - Present\n|}\n\n== External Links ==\n[https://ucsmub.edu.mm Official website]\n\n[http://ucsmbn.moe.edu.mm/ Subdomain] of [[Ministry of Education (Myanmar)|Ministry of Education, Myanmar]]\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n<br />\n\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Computer Universities in Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Ayeyarwady Region]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2003]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox university\n| name = University of Computer Studies (Maubin)\n| native_name = \u1000\u103d\u1014\u103a\u1015\u103b\u1030\u1010\u102c\u1010\u1000\u1039\u1000\u101e\u102d\u102f\u101c\u103a(\u1019\u1021\u1030\u1015\u1004\u103a)\n| native_name_lang = my\n| former_name = Computer College (Maubin)\n| motto = \u1019\u103c\u1014\u103a\u1019\u103e\u1014\u103a\u1010\u103d\u1000\u103a\u1001\u103b\u1000\u103a \u1010\u102d\u102f\u1004\u103a\u1038\u1015\u103c\u100a\u103a\u1010\u103d\u1000\u103a\n| motto_lang = my\n| established = {{start date and age|2003}}\n| type = Public\n| affiliation = [[Ministry of Education (Science and Technology)]]\n| rector = Professor Dr. Thandar Thein\n| address = Between Block 1 and Block 2, Sein Mya Kan Thar Road\n| city = [[Ma-ubin|Maubin]]\n| state = [[Ayeyarwaddy|Ayeyarwaddy Region]]\n| country = [[Myanmar]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|16|44|28.1|N|95|39|05.1|E|type:edu|display=inline}}\n| colours = [[Turquoise]]   {{color box|turquoise}}\n| website = https://ucsmub.edu.mm/\n| logo = UCSMUB Logo.png\n}}\n\n'''University of Computer Studies (Maubin)''' ({{Lang-my|\u1000\u103d\u1014\u103a\u1015\u103b\u1030\u1010\u102c\u1010\u1000\u1039\u1000\u101e\u102d\u102f\u101c\u103a(\u1019\u1021\u1030\u1015\u1004\u103a)}} {{IPA-my|k\u028a\u0300\u0270\u0303pj\u00f9t\u00e0 t\u025b\u0294k\u0259\u03b8\u00f2 (m\u0259\u0294\u00f9b\u026a\u0300\u0270\u0303 mjo\u0330)}}) is situated on Seinmya Kanthar Street between No. (1) ward and No. (2) ward in [[Ma-ubin|Maubin]], [[Ma-ubin District|Maubin district]], [[Ayeyarwady Region|Ayeyarwaddy Region]], [[Myanmar]]. It extends as far as 42.552 acres.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://ucsmbn.moe.edu.mm/?page_id=8|title=BackGround History \u00bb Computer University (Maubin)|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n'''Government Computer College (Maubin)''' started up on first January 2003. It was upgraded as '''Computer University (Maubin)''' on 20<sup>th</sup> January 2007.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Citation|title=\u1000\u103d\u1014\u103a\u1015\u103b\u1030\u1010\u102c\u1010\u1000\u1039\u1000\u101e\u102d\u102f\u101c\u103a(\u1019\u1021\u1030\u1015\u1004\u103a)|date=2019-06-05|url=https://my.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=%E1%80%80%E1%80%BD%E1%80%94%E1%80%BA%E1%80%95%E1%80%BB%E1%80%B0%E1%80%90%E1%80%AC%E1%80%90%E1%80%80%E1%80%B9%E1%80%80%E1%80%9E%E1%80%AD%E1%80%AF%E1%80%9C%E1%80%BA(%E1%80%99%E1%80%A1%E1%80%B0%E1%80%95%E1%80%84%E1%80%BA)&oldid=461891|work=\u101d\u102e\u1000\u102e\u1015\u102e\u1038\u1012\u102e\u1038\u101a\u102c\u1038|language=my|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref> In 2015, It was renamed as '''University of Computer Studies (Maubin)'''.\n\n== Bachelor Degree ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Degree Programmes\n!No\n!Name\n!Type\n!Duration\n|-\n|1\n|B.C.Sc (Bachelor of Computer Science)\n|Bachelor\n|5 Years\n|-\n|2\n|B.C.Tech (Bachelor of Computer Technology)\n|Bachelor\n|5 Years\n|-\n|3\n|D.C.Sc. (Diploma in Computer Science)\n|Post Graduate\n|1 Year\n|}\n\n== Faculty ==\n\n=== '''Academic Faculties'''\u200b ===\n\n# Faculty of Computer Science\n# Faculty of Information Science\n# Faculty of Computing\n# Faculty of Computer System and Technology\n# Faculty of Natural Science\n# Faculty of Languages\n#* Department of Myanmar\n#* Department of English\n# Department of Information Technology Supporting and Maintenance\n#* Department of Application\n\n=== '''Management Departments''' ===\n\n# Staff Affair Department\n# Student Affair Department\n# Finance Department\n# Estate Department\n\n== Rectors/Principals ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Rectors/Principals of UCSMUB\n!No\n!Name\n!Role\n!Active (MM/YYY)\n|-\n|1\n|Daw Moe Moe Win\n|Principal\n|01/2003 - 11/2003\n|-\n|2\n|Dr. Tar Khin\n|Principal\n|11/2003 - 09/2004\n|-\n|3\n|Dr. Mie Mie Su Thwin\n|Principal\n|09/2004 - 10/2005\n|-\n|4\n|Dr. Thin Thin Htike\n|Principal\n|10/2005 - 05/2006\n|-\n|5\n|Dr. Hla Myat Kaung\n|Principal\n|05/2006 - 07/2008\n|-\n|6\n|Dr. Hinn Min Oo\n|Principal\n|08/2008 - 07/2010\n|-\n|7\n|Dr. Thae Nu Phyu\n|Principal\n|07/2010 - 01/2013\n|-\n|8\n|Dr. Khaing Khaing Oo\n|Principal\n|01/2013 - 04/2015\n|-\n|9\n|Dr. Thandar Thein\n|Rector\n|02/2015 - Present\n|}\n\n== External Links ==\n[https://ucsmub.edu.mm Official website]\n\n[http://ucsmbn.moe.edu.mm/ Subdomain] of [[Ministry of Education (Myanmar)|Ministry of Education, Myanmar]]\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n<br />\n\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Computer Universities in Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Myanmar]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Ayeyarwady Region]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2003]]\n", "name_user": "Hnhtag", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Computer_Studies_(Maubin)"}
{"title_page": "Seleya River", "text_new": "{{Infobox river\n  | name              = Seleya River\n  | image             = \n  | image_size        = \n  | image_alt         =\n  | image_caption     = \n  | map               = \n  | map_size          = \n  | map_alt           =\n  | map_caption       = \n  | source1_location  = \n  | mouth_location    = [[Kolva River (Perm Krai)|Kolva River]]\n  | subdivision_type1 = Country\n  | subdivision_name1 = [[Russia]]\n  | progression       = {{RKolva}}\n  | length            = {{convert|20|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n  | source1_elevation = \n  | mouth_elevation   = \n  | discharge1_avg    = \n  | basin_size        = \n  | river_system      = \n  | tributaries_left  =\n  | tributaries_right =\n}}\n'''Seleya''' ({{lang-ru|\u0421\u0435\u043b\u0435\u044f}}) is a river in [[Perm Krai]], [[Russia]], a [[:left bank|left]] tributary of the [[Kolva River (Perm Krai)|Kolva River]], which in turn is a tributary of the [[Vishera River (Perm Krai)|Vishera River]]. The river is {{convert|20|km|mi}} long.<ref name='\u041c\u041f\u0420 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438'>{{cite web|url=http://textual.ru/gvr/index.php?card=180492|title=\u0413\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0440 \u0420\u0424: \u0421\u0435\u043b\u0435\u044f}}</ref> It flows into the Kolva River {{convert|351|km|mi}} from the Kolva's mouth.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Perm Krai}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Perm Krai]]\n\n\n{{PermKrai-geo-stub}}\n{{Russia-river-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox river\n  | name              = Seleya River\n  | image             = \n  | image_size        = \n  | image_alt         =\n  | image_caption     = \n  | map               = \n  | map_size          = \n  | map_alt           =\n  | map_caption       = \n  | source1_location  = \n  | mouth_location    = [[Kolva River (Perm Krai)|Kolva River]]\n  | subdivision_type1 = Country\n  | subdivision_name1 = [[Russia]]\n  | progression       = \n  | length            = {{convert|20|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n  | source1_elevation = \n  | mouth_elevation   = \n  | discharge1_avg    = \n  | basin_size        = \n  | river_system      = \n  | tributaries_left  =\n  | tributaries_right =\n}}\n'''Seleya''' ({{lang-ru|\u0421\u0435\u043b\u0435\u044f}}) is a river in [[Perm Krai]], [[Russia]], a [[:left bank|left]] tributary of the [[Kolva River (Perm Krai)|Kolva River]], which in turn is a tributary of the [[Vishera River (Perm Krai)|Vishera River]]. The river is {{convert|20|km|mi}} long.<ref name='\u041c\u041f\u0420 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438'>{{cite web|url=http://textual.ru/gvr/index.php?card=180492|title=\u0413\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0432\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0440\u0435\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0440 \u0420\u0424: \u0421\u0435\u043b\u0435\u044f}}</ref> It flows into the Kolva River {{convert|351|km|mi}} from the Kolva's mouth.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{coord missing|Perm Krai}}\n\n[[Category:Rivers of Perm Krai]]\n\n\n{{PermKrai-geo-stub}}\n{{Russia-river-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "progression", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seleya_River"}
{"title_page": "Gusinje", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields that may be available-->\n<!--See the Table at Infobox settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|name                   =Gusinje<!-- at least one of the first two fields must be filled in -->\n| settlement_type      = [[List of cities in Montenegro|Town]] and [[Municipalities of Montenegro|municipality]]\n|native_name            = \u0413\u0443\u0441\u0438\u045a\u0435<br>Gucia\n|other name              =\n|total_type             = <!-- to set a non-standard label for total area and population rows -->\n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline          = Plav from Air.jpg\n|imagesize              = 250px\n|image_caption          = Towns of Gusinje (front) and [[Plav, Montenegro|Plav]] (background), seen from air.\n|image_flag             = \n|flag_size              =\n|image_seal             = \u0413\u0440\u0431 \u043e\u043f\u0448\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0435 \u0413\u0443\u0441\u0438\u045a\u0435.jpg\n|seal_size              = \n|image_shield           = \n|shield_size            = \n|image_blank_emblem     =\n|blank_emblem_type      =\n|blank_emblem_size      =\n|image_map              = \n|mapsize                = \n|map_caption            = \n|image_map1             = \n|mapsize1               = \n|map_caption1           = \n|image_dot_map          =\n|pushpin_map            =Montenegro \n|pushpin_label_position = <!-- the position of the pushpin label: left, right, top, bottom, none -->\n|pushpin_map_caption    =\n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type       =Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Montenegro}}\n|subdivision_type1      = Municipality\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Gusinje Municipality]]\n|subdivision_type2      = \n|subdivision_name2      = \n<!-- Smaller parts (e.g. boroughs of a city) and seat of government -->\n|seat_type              =\n|seat                   =\n|parts_type             =\n|parts_style            = <!-- =list (for list), coll (for collapsed list), para (for paragraph format)\n                               Default is list if up to 5 items, coll if more than 5-->\n|parts                  = <!-- parts text, or header for parts list -->\n|p1                     =\n|p2                     = <!-- etc. up to p50: for separate parts to be listed--> \n<!-- Politics ----------------->\n|government_footnotes   =\n|government_type        =\n|leader_title           =\n|leader_name            =  <!--add   (no-break space) to leader names to disable automatic links-->\n|leader_title1          =  \n|leader_name1           =\n|established_title      =  <!-- Settled -->\n|established_date       = \n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|area_magnitude         = \n|unit_pref                = <!--Enter: Imperial, to display imperial  before metric-->\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = 3.73\n|area_land_km2            = <!--See table @ Template:Infobox settlement for details on unit conversion-->\n|area_water_km2           =\n|area_total_sq_mi         =\n|area_land_sq_mi          =\n|area_water_sq_mi         =\n|area_water_percent       =\n<!-- Elevation -------------------------->\n|elevation_footnotes    =  <!--for references: use <ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            = 1014\n|elevation_ft           =\n|elevation_max_m            = \n|elevation_max_ft           =\n|elevation_min_m            = \n|elevation_min_ft           =\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of               =2011\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_note                =\n|population_total               =1673\n|population_density_km2         = <!--For automatic calculation, any density field may contain: auto -->\n|population_density_sq_mi       =\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone               = [[Central European Time|CET]]\n|utc_offset             = +1\n|timezone_DST           = [[Central European Summer Time|CEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST         = +2\n|coor_type              = <!-- can be used to specify what the coordinates refer to -->\n|coordinates            = {{coord|42|33|43|N|19|50|02|E|region:ME|display=inline}}\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|postal_code_type       =  <!-- enter ZIP code, Postcode, Post code, Postal code... -->\n|postal_code            =\n|area_code              =\n|blank_name             = [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|Climate]]\n|blank_info             = [[Oceanic climate|Cfb]]\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n| registration_plate     = [[Vehicle registration plates of Montenegro|GS]]\n}}\n\n'''Gusinje''' ([[Montenegrin Cyrillic]]: \u0413\u0443\u0441\u0438\u045a\u0435 {{IPA-sh|\u0261\u01d4si\u0272e|pron}}, {{lang-sq|Gucia}})  is a small [[town]] in north-eastern [[Montenegro]]. According to the 2011 census, the town has a population of 1,673 and is the administrative center of [[Gusinje Municipality]].\n\n==Name==\nTwo alternative etymologies have been proposed for the toponym ''Gusinje''. One links it to Slavic ''guska'' ([[goose]]), the other to an Illyrian word ''Geusiae'' from which the [[Albanian language|Albanian]] name of the town, ''Guci(a)'', would have evolved.<ref name=\"Opstina16\"/><ref name=\"Loma70\">{{harvnb|Loma|2013|p=70}}</ref> In archival records, it has been recorded variably as ''Gousino'' (\u0413\u043e\u0443\u0441\u0438\u043d\u043e), ''Gustigne'' (1614) in Venetian archives, ''Gusna'' (\u06af\u0648\u0633\u0646) and ''Gusinye'' in Ottoman Turkish.<ref name=\"Loma70\"/><ref name=\"Elsie151\"/>\n\n==Geography==\n{{main|Gusinje Municipality}}\nThe town is located in the Plav-Gusinje area, part of the upper [[Lim (river)|Lim]] valley in the [[Prokletije]] range at an elevation of ca. 1,014 m. [[Zla Kolata]], the highest mountain in Montenegro about 10km south of Gusinje in the National Park \"Prokletije\".<ref>{{Cite web|title = NACIONALNI PARK PROKLETIJE|url = http://www.nparkovi.me/sajt/np-prokletije|website = www.nparkovi.me|access-date = 2016-01-14}}</ref> Gusinje is traversed by the [[Vermosh River]] into which pours the [[Vruja Creek]] as it moves eastwards towards [[Plav, Montenegro|Plav]]. Vruja is formed at [[Ali Pasha of Gusinje|Ali Pasha]]'s wellsprings (''Alipa\u0161ini izvori''/''Krojet e Ali Pash\u00ebs'') about 2km south of Gusinje's center. The part of Vermosh between the location where it meets Vruja and Plav is locally called ''Luca''. Vermosh then pours into [[Lake Plav]]. It is the first tributary of [[Lim (river)|Lim]]. Gusinje is the seat of the municipality of the same name. From 1953 to 2014, it was part of [[Plav Municipality]]. In 2014, it became again a distinct municipality. The town's boundaries form ~3.73 km\u00b2 of the total 157 km\u00b2 of the municipality.{{sfn|Opstina Gusinje|2012|p=5}} Much of the area of the municipality is mountainous land used in the past for livestock herding.\n\n==History==\nIt is known that a medieval settlement was located in the territory of present-day Gusinje. Gusinje was mentioned as a caravan station on the Ragusa-Cattaro\u2013Scutari\u2013Pe\u0107 route, in the 14th century.<ref name=\"Opstina16\">{{harvnb|Opstina Gusinje|2012|p=16}}</ref>{{sfn|Zajednica osnovnog obrazovanja i vaspitanja|1986|p=137}} In historical record, Gusinje appears in 1485 in the defter of the [[sanjak of Scutari]] as a village in the [[vilayet]] of Plav, a ''[[Hass (Ottoman)|hass-\u0131 h\u00fcmayun]]'' (imperial domain) that stood directly under the Ottoman Sultan. It had 96 households, 21 unmarried men and four widows.{{sfn|Pulaha|1974|p=99}} This is was a big settlement compared to other villages in Montenegro and northern Albania. Relatively to other neighbouring regions, the Plav-Gusinje area in general was densely populated at the end of the 15th century with 15 villages and over a thousand households in total.{{sfn|Pulaha|1974|p=112}}\n\nGusinje stood at the intersection of the Ottoman trade routes between northern Albania, Montenegro and Kosovo. Thus, the trade that passed through Gusinje generated much wealth for the Sultan, the beys and the local [[sipahi]]s that were granted taxing rights. This made the trade route a constant target for the neighbouring Albanian tribe (''fis'') of [[Kelmendi (tribe)|Kelmendi]], which was in rebellion against the Ottomans and was plundering their trade routes. Venetian diplomat [[Mariano Bolizza]] who travelled in the region reported that at the end of 1612 the building of the fortress of Gusinje - around which the modern town developed - was completed.<ref name=\"Elsie151\"/> The location was chosen because it stands at the convergence of all pathways from Kelmendi. Thus, modern Gusinje stands ~6km to the west and ~10km to the north of the routes from Kelmendi to modern [[Sandzak]]. The fortress was built at the reguest of Sem Zaus, the Ottoman bey of Podgorica who wanted to stop the attacks of Kelmendi and to be able to travel freely in his domain. In 1614, Mariano Bolizza reported that the village had 100 households and a garrisson of 237 men under Belo Juvanin.<ref name=\"Elsie151\">{{harvnb|Elsie|2003|p=151}}</ref> The fortress was also designed to stop the expansion of the [[Ku\u010di]] tribe in the Upper Lim valley.\n\nIn time despite initial Ottoman resistance, Kelmendi and Ku\u010di and other communities came to form many of the historical neighbourhoods ([[mahalla]]) of Gusinje of today. Their descendants although initially Christian, willingly or forcefully converted to Islam by the middle 18th century. An important family - which later developed into a brotherhood - in the development of Gusinje is that of the Omeragaj (today known as Omeragi\u0107)  from [[Shala (tribe)|Shala]] who appeared in the village in the early 18th century {{sfn|Dedushaj|2012|p=18}}. The different mosques of Gusinje today represent the different brotherhoods that built them. For example, the Cekaj mosque (''\u010ceki\u0107a d\u017eamija''/''xhamia e Cekajve'') was built by the Cekaj brotherhood of Kelmendi in 1687, while the New Mosque built in 1899 is known as ''Radon\u010di\u0107a'' after the Radon\u010di\u0107i brotherhood of Ku\u010di. At the beginning of the 18th century, Gusinje was the seat of the local [[kadiluk]]. In terms of military administration, the captaincy of Gusinje was part of the [[Bosnia Eyalet]] in 1724. Central Ottoman administration collapsed in the decades to come and the [[Pashalik of Scutari|Pashalik of Shkodra]] emerged as a regional power. The Vezir's mosque, built by [[Kara Mahmud Bushati]] in 1765 in the town center is a symbol of the Pashalik's lead in the upper Lim valley. Its downfall in 1831 brought back actual Ottoman rule. In 1852, in the register of the [[Kosovo Vilayet]], Gusinje is recorded with 1,500 households. It was a developing town that had 350 shops, eight [[madrasa]]s and five mosques. The captaincy of Gusinje in 1869 was part of the [[sanjak of Prizren]].<ref name=\"Opstina16\"/>\n\nAs the Ottoman Empire disintegrated in the long 19th century already in the [[Treaty of San Stefano]], Gusinje and Plav were awarded to the independent [[Principality of Montenegro]]. Gusinje was developing as a commercial town at the time, but still remained outside properly established rule of Ottoman law. Gun ownership was widespread and Ottoman rule was difficult to enforce.{{sfn|Gawrych|2006|p=61}} The Albanians of Gusinje opposed the decisions of the treaty and sent telegrams of protest to the embassies of the [[Great Powers]].{{sfn|Gawrych|2006|p=44}} In the [[Congress of Berlin]] and [[Treaty of Berlin (1878)|its final treaty]] those decisions were finalized. The Albanians in the two regions reacted against the final decision in favor annexation and formed the [[League of Prizren]]. \n\nA noted figure of the League of Prizren was [[Ali Pasha of Gusinje|Ali Pasha Shabanagaj]], a landowner and military commander from Gusinje. In the ensuing [[Battle of Nov\u0161i\u0107e]] the League of Prizren led by Shabanagaj defeated the approaching Montenegrin forces led by [[Marko Miljanov]].{{sfn|Gawrych|2006|p=62}} More than 140 dead and wounded of the ~300 casualties of the League of Prizren in the battle were from Gusinje. Ismail Omeraga, commander of the Gusinje volunteers died in the battle. His head was carried back in [[Cetinje]]. {{sfn|Dedushaj|2012|p=19}} Reports after the battle claim that the victors carried into the town 60 heads from their defeated foes. The annexation was effectively stopped and the Great Powers began another round of negotiations which eventually led to [[Ulcinj]]'s annexation by Montenegro as compensation. The battle became a point of reference in the [[Albanian National Awakening]] and set a precedent about the need of armed struggle to defend other areas.{{sfn|Gawrych|2006|p=74}} Although the battle took place near Nov\u0161i\u0107e which is ~4km to the north of Plav, in the Ottoman press of the time it became known as ''Gusinye hadisesi'' (Gusinye Incident) because of its crucial role in the struggle. \n\nIn 1893, Gusinje had 1,600 households, 5 mosques and 240 shops.<ref name=\"Opstina16\"/> The districts were part of the [[Sanjak of Novi Pazar]] of the [[Kosovo Vilayet]] until 1913. In the aftermath of the Balkan Wars, Gusinje became a subject of dispute between newly independent Albania and Montenegro. [[Nicholas I of Montenegro]] in the [[London Conference of 1912\u201313|London Peace Conference]] asked for the region of [[Kelmendi (tribe)|Kelmendi]] as otherwise communication between the capital of [[Podgorica]] and the new eastern provinces of Montenegro would be blocked. As Kelmendi finally became part of Albania, Gusinje was given to Montenegro with the provision that the people of Kelmendi would have free passage to the town.{{sfn|Cornwall|1987|pp=6-12}} About 2000 Albanian refugees from Gusinje and Plav were reported in Shkodra in 1913 by the director of the Red Cross which was stationed in the city. The beginning of WWI in practice stopped the implementation of any agreement. In 1919, the decision was reaffirmed but the border was closed. In Albania, the closing of the border between [[Mal\u00ebsia]] and Gusinje has been seen as a main cause for the interwar impoverishment of areas like Kelmendi and [[Shala]], which were deprived from access to their traditional market town.{{sfn|Galaty|2013|p=56}}\n\nThe entry of the Montenegrin army in 1913 and the Yugoslav army after 1919 in Gusinje was accompanied by repressive policies against the local population. In 1919, Ro\u017eaje was one of the centres of the [[Plav rebellion]] (''Plavska pobuna'') that fought against the inclusion of [[Sandzak]] in the [[Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes]].{{sfn|Morrison|2018|p=56}} About 450 Muslim locals were killed in Gusinje and nearby Plav after the uprising was quelled.{{sfn|Morrison|2018|p=21}} These events remain a matter of dispute in modern Montenegrin politics. In 2013, the President of Montenegro [[Filip Vujanovi\u0107]] made the first direct acknowledgment of the events in a ceremony in [[Berane]] where he declared that ''the crimes performed in Plav and Gusinje are the dark side of the Montenegrin history''.{{sfn|Pacariz|2013|p=437}}\n\nGusinje became part of Albania in WWII by Fascist Italy and then Nazi Germany to win the support of the local population. After the war, the 1913 borders were reaffirmed. Gusinje's status as a distinct municipality was revoked in 1953. Along with other reasons it fueled immigration and impoverishment in the town and the municipality.{{sfn|Opstina Gusinje|2012|p=17}} In 2014, Gusinje regained its municipal status.\n\n== Monuments ==\nIn Gusinje there are a number of historical mosques in Montenegro. The oldest preserved mosque in the town is \u010ceki\u0107a d\u017eamija or xhamia e Cekajve built by the Cekaj brotherhood of Kelmendi. The second oldest is the Vezir's mosque (vezirova d\u017eamija/xhamia e vezirit) built by [[Kara Mahmud Bushati]] in 1765 on the existing site of another mosque originally built in 1626. The New Mosque (nova d\u017eamija/xhamia e re) also known as Radon\u010di\u0107a was built by the Radon\u010di\u0107i brotherhood of Ku\u0107i in 1899. There are also a number of mosques whose ruins only remain today. The mosque of Sultan [[Ahmed I]] was built during his reign between 1603 and 1617. It was burnt in 1746-47. Another ruined mosque is that built by the Gjylbegaj family (a branch of the [[Begolli family]]). It was built in 1833.{{sfn|Had\u017ei\u0107|2018|p=11}}\n\n==Demographics==\nSince 1913, Gusinje has experienced many waves of immigration in the 20th century. These have depopulated it as a result in the 21st century. The municipality of Gusinje reports that 18,400 people trace theirs origins to the town of Gusinje out of a total diaspora of ~30,000 from the Gusinje area. They mostly live in the US.{{sfn|Opstina Gusinje|2012|p=18}} Gusinje is almost entirely Muslim and either Albanian-speaking or Slavic-speaking. The Slavic dialect of Gusinje and Plav shows very high structural influence from Albanian. Its uniqueness in terms of language contact between Albanian and Slavic is explained by the fact that most Slavic-speakers in today's Gusinje are of Albanian origin.{{sfn|Curtis|2012|p=40}}\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! colspan=3| Ethnic groups (2011 census)\n|-\n!width=\"100px\"|Ethnic group\n!width=\"80px\"|Number\n!width=\"80px\"|Percentage\n|-\n| [[Bosniaks in Montenegro|Bosniaks]] || 1,098 || 65.63%\n|-\n| [[Muslims by nationality|Muslims]] || 294 || 17.57%\n|-\n| [[Albanians in Montenegro|Albanians]] || 182 || 10.88%\n|-\n| [[Montenegrins]] || 46 || 2.75%\n|-\n| [[Serbs of Montenegro|Serbs]] || 28 || 1.67%\n|-\n| Other/undeclared || 25 || 1.49%\n|-\n| '''Total''' || '''1,673'''|| '''100%'''\n|}\n\n{{Col-2}}\n{{historical populations|align=non\n|1948 | 2,402\n|1953 | 2,555\n|1961 | 2,756\n|1971 | 2,695\n|1981 | 2,625\n|1991 | 2,472\n|2003 | 1,704\n|2011 | 1,673\n}}\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==Notable people==\n<!-- ONLY ADD A PERSON TO THIS LIST IF THEY ALREADY HAVE AN ARTICLE IN THE ENGLISH WIKIPEDIA -->\n* [[Ali Pasha of Gusinje]], Ottoman governor \n* [[D\u017eenan Radon\u010di\u0107]], Montenegrin footballer\n* [[Fahrudin Radon\u010di\u0107]], Montenegrin businessman, founder of [[Dnevni Avaz]] in Bosnia and Herzegovina\n* [[Ramo Kolenovi\u0107]], kayaker\n* [[Dino Radon\u010di\u0107]], basketball player\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite journal |last1=Cornwall |first1=Mark |title=Between two wars. King Nikola of Montenegro and the Great Powers, 1913-1914 |journal=The South Slav Journal |volume=IX |issue=1-2 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CBpXAAAAYAAJ |date=1987 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Curtis |first1=Matthew |title=Slavic-Albanian Language Contact, Convergence, and Coexistence |date=2012 |publisher=Ohio State Unviersity |isbn=978-1-2675-8033-7 |url=https://eric.ed.gov/?id=ED546136 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Dedushaj |first1=Rexhep |title=100 vjet luft\u00eb |date=2012 |publisher=New York |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/200396068/100-vjet-Lufte |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Elsie|first=Robert|title=Early Albania: A reader of Historical texts, 11th\u201317th centuries|year=2003|location=Wiesbaden|publisher=Otto Harrassowitz Verlag|url=https://books.google.com/?id=_sHmTRCEe7kC&printsec|isbn=9783447047838|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Galaty |first1=Michael |last2=Lafe |first2=Ols |last3=Lee |first3=Wayne |last4=Tafilica |first4=Zamir |title=Light and Shadow: Isolation and Interaction in the Shala Valley of Northern Albania |date=2013 |publisher=The Cotsen Institute of Archaeology Press |isbn=1931745714 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f2mRDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA73 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gawrych|first=George|title=The Crescent and the Eagle: Ottoman rule, 